{"session_id": "2fd36ba5-ba5e-49de-ba15-f78653c66946", "transcript_path": "C:\\Users\\enyan\\.claude\\projects\\d--projects-claudeCodeLearn-python-sdk-main\\2fd36ba5-ba5e-49de-ba15-f78653c66946.jsonl", "cwd": "d:\\projects\\claudeCodeLearn\\python-sdk-main", "permission_mode": "default", "hook_event_name": "Stop", "stop_hook_active": false, "last_assistant_message": "Based on my exploration of the codebase, here's what this project does:\n\n## MCP Python SDK\n\nThis is the official Python SDK for the **Model Context Protocol (MCP)** \udce2\udc80\udc94 a standard protocol for connecting LLM applications to external tools, data sources, and capabilities.\n\n---\n\n### Core Concept\n\nMCP separates two concerns:\n- **Servers** expose capabilities (tools, resources, prompts) to LLM clients\n- **Clients** connect to servers and invoke those capabilities on behalf of an LLM\n\n---\n\n### What Servers Can Expose\n\n| Primitive | Description |\n|-----------|-------------|\n| **Tools** | Callable functions an LLM can invoke (e.g. `add(a, b)`, `search(query)`) |\n| **Resources** | Data/content the LLM can read (e.g. `file://path`, `greeting://{name}`) |\n| **Prompts** | Pre-built prompt templates with arguments |\n\n---\n\n### Two Server APIs\n\n**High-level `MCPServer`** \udce2\udc80\udc94 decorator-based, designed for application developers:\n```python\nmcp = MCPServer(\"MyServer\")\n\n@mcp.tool()\ndef add(a: int, b: int) -> int: ...\n\n@mcp.resource(\"data://{id}\")\ndef get_data(id: str) -> str: ...\n\n@mcp.prompt()\ndef summarize(text: str) -> str: ...\n```\n\n**Low-level `Server`** \udce2\udc80\udc94 explicit handler registration, full control over the protocol:\n```python\nserver = Server(\"MyServer\", on_list_tools=..., on_call_tool=...)\n```\n\n---\n\n### Transport Options\n\nServers can be reached over multiple transports:\n\n- **stdio** \udce2\udc80\udc94 process-based, used by Claude Desktop and CLI tools\n- **Streamable HTTP** \udce2\udc80\udc94 primary HTTP transport for web deployments\n- **SSE** (Server-Sent Events) \udce2\udc80\udc94 legacy HTTP transport\n- **WebSocket** \udce2\udc80\udc94 for real-time bidirectional use cases\n- **In-memory** \udce2\udc80\udc94 no network, for testing only\n\n---\n\n### Client\n\nThe `Client` class is a unified high-level client that handles transport lifecycle automatically. It accepts a server instance (in-memory), a URL (HTTP), or a custom transport:\n\n```python\nasync with Client(server) as client:       # in-memory (testing)\n    result = await client.call_tool(\"add\", {\"a\": 1, \"b\": 2})\n\nasync with Client(\"http://localhost:8000/mcp\") as client:  # HTTP\n    tools = await client.list_tools()\n```\n\n---\n\n### Authentication\n\nBuilt-in OAuth 2.0 support on both sides:\n- **Server-side**: full OAuth authorization server (authorize, token, revoke, metadata endpoints) with a provider interface you implement\n- **Client-side**: OAuth 2.0 client flow including the `client_credentials` extension\n\n---\n\n### Experimental Features\n\n- **Tasks** \udce2\udc80\udc94 long-running async tasks with streaming updates and polling, allowing servers to push progress back to clients\n\n---\n\n### CLI Tooling\n\nThe `mcp` CLI (installed via `mcp[cli]`) provides:\n- `mcp dev` \udce2\udc80\udc94 run a server in development mode with hot reload\n- `mcp install` \udce2\udc80\udc94 register a server with Claude Desktop\n- `mcp run` \udce2\udc80\udc94 run a server directly\n\n---\n\n### Current Status\n\nThe `main` branch is **v2 (pre-alpha)**. `v1.x` is the current stable release. v2 is a breaking rework \udce2\udc80\udc94 old `@deprecated` shims are not kept; removed APIs are deleted outright and documented in [docs/migration.md](docs/migration.md)."}
